@node Intro "Introduction"


@{b}Introduction@{ub}


	This script, when invoked, will ask the user for a picture file, obtain the
@{APEN 4}WIDTH@{APEN 1}, @{APEN 4}HEIGHT@{APEN 1}, @{APEN 4}BORDER@{APEN 1} condition,
@{APEN 4}ALT@{APEN 1}ernate text and @{APEN 4}ALIGN@{APEN 1}ment information and
then insert all this information into an HTML @{APEN 4}<IMG SRC...>@{APEN 1} tag.

@endnode
@node req "Requirements"


@{b}Requirements@{ub}


Needed to run this script:


	@{APEN 4}Rexxmast@{APEN 1} running in the background.

	@{APEN 4}CygnusEd Pro@{APEN 1} v4. There seems to be a bug in v4.15 that does
not allow invoking of AREXX scripts from the menu. You can work around this by
invoking the script from a shell. This bug is not present in v4.17 however there 
is another bug that deletes a files icon if one exists when you save the file.
Just backup your icons if you have some nice ones that you wish to keep.

	@{APEN 4}Viewtek@{APEN 1} v2.1

		available on Aminet in the @{u}pics/show@{uu} directory.

	@{APEN 4}RexReqTools@{APEN 1} v1.3

		available on Aminet in the @{u}util/rexx@{uu} directory.

@endnode

@node use "Usage"


@{b}Usage@{ub}


	Copy the script to your REXX: directory or a dedicated CEDPro Arexx directory
that you use.

This script is most useful when attached to a function key within CygnusEd Pro.

Go to the @{APEN 4}DOS/ARexx interface@{APEN 1} submenu in the @{APEN 4}
Special@{APEN 1} menu and select @{APEN 4}Install DOS/ARexx Command...
@{APEN 1}. Then choose which function key to assign the script to. Type
the name of the script 'pictag.ced' and hit Return.



@{B}NOTES:@{UB}


1. The image type is limited to JPEGs, GIFs and now PNGs which should pretty
much cover all HTML needs. The PNG and GIF support does not use Viewtek - 
I found out how to read the image size from the file. I am still working on
this for JPEGs. When using Viewtek (for JPEGs) the image size is limited to 
9999 x 9999 pixels which, I think should not pose a problem.


2. There is very little (none) error trapping or checking. The script is simple
enough such that if you feed it a non-image file it will just stop executing
and no harm should come to the HTML file.


3. It is important (and logical) to have the pictures that one is referencing
stored in either the same directory or a sub-directory as the HTML file. If
this is not the case (eg. you are loading files from another drive) then
either the script or the tag will have to be edited.
This is a personal preference but, I feel it is a practical and normal way of
structuring ones HTML and graphics files.

**** This has been improved ****  See @{"History" link history}.

Example: In the following directory structure listing, the HTML files should
all refer to pictures in the 'pics' directory.


		volume		Work:

		dir				<HTML>

			file				index.HTML

			file				page1.HTML

			file				page2.HTML

			dir				<pics>

			file					picture1.jpg

			file					picture2.jpg

			file					picture3.jpg


@endnode

